title: The Excruciation Exam
description: The Excruciation Exam is part of the TMBRA Marathon Series. Single track laps at both Bluff Creek Ranch and Rocky Hill Ranch, then gravel and paved roads connecting them.
course: Racers will do an approximately 8 mile lap at Bluff Creek Ranch, then head to Rocky Hill Ranch on gravel and paved roads. Reaching Rocky Hill, they will do an approximately 12 mile lap there, then return to Warda on a different route. Total distance around 80 miles.
registration: Pre-reg at Bikereg.com or register onsite for $10 more on the Friday night before the race. NO REGISTRATION the morning of the race. Entry fee includes the day use fees for both ranches ($10 each)
notes: There will be four checkpoints, one on the way to RHR, two coming in and out of RHR, then one more on the way back to BCR. There will be neutral food and water at these stations and these are the ONLY places where personal feeds are allowed. In addition, we will transport bags from the race start at Warda over to Rocky Hill for the racers, then return them to Warda. NO ice chests here, please pack a small bag for this purpose.

title: 2016 GHORBA Even Bigger Big Ring Challenge
Texas Chainring Massacre
description:
No license required!

The Texas Chainring Massacre is a full on gravel grinder featuring a unique combination of dirt roads and desolate country roads that promises to be both scenic and challenging. Riders will be able to enjoy a fantastic route that starts and ends in the "civilized" part of the D/FW Metroplex near Valley View, TX while meandering through some scenic rural areas.


This marked course ride will provide neutral aid/support station at the 50 mile mark but no outside support is allowed except at the aid station. Plan to bring enough food and supplies to be self supported in case of break down since it might take several hours for a sweep/sag vehicle to reach stranded riders. 9am start time in Valley View, TX.


All roads whether paved or unpaved are public roads subject to the regulations of the great State of Texas. Participants are required to obey all "rules of the road" and laws for the applicable jurisdiction(s) in which they operate their bicycles and/or other vehicles. This applies to both the featured event as well as any practice or warm up events. The Texas Chainring Massacre is an all-weather event unless conditions are deemed unsafe for riders so there is a no refunds policy.


Promoter may modify the course at any time for rider safety or based on course conditions

Day of registration for all categories will be $50.
course: Gravel/dirt roads. Rout is marked

title: Ladies Beginner Track Riding/Racing Session
description:
LADIES: COME LEARN TO RIDE and RACE the TRACK, HAVE FUN, WIN STUFF!!!

Are you a woman who likes to race/ride bikes? Have you been looking for an excuse to come check out the track? Join us for a Ladies Beginner Session at Alkek Velodrome! Come learn to ride and race in a supportive and positive environment. Track racing is fun and exciting - there are disciplines for sprinters and endurance riders alike, individual events, team events, and mass start events (think NASCAR on bikes).

This beginner session at Alkek is all about getting women comfortable on fixed gear bikes, acquainted with track rules and etiquette, and learning bike handling skills that are important to track riding and useful in ALL cycling disciplines, from commuting to crit racing. In addition, you will learn about the types of races we do, the rules of racing, and details about the upcoming race season (starting in early spring).

And what better way to learn than surrounded by a group of awesome, supportive, women racers and officials???

The team of Alkek lady racers (representing multiple Houston Area Cycling Teams) will run the session and we will all be there to create our own peer field for riding and learning. In addition, our very own USA Cycling Official, Cyndi Smith, will be on hand to review racing rules and officiate our training races during the session.

Successful completion of the training session will prepare and certify you to participate in the Alkek Velodrome's Friday Night Racing series that runs through the spring, summer and fall, as well as a number of Texas Cup racing events at the Alkek Velodrome this season. 

In addition to the opportunity to learn about track racing from a positive and supportive group of women, you will have the opportunity to win some great prizes and enjoy some of Cyndi Smith's amazing treats. Come join us and bring your lady friends.

What you need to bring: 
•	Helmet (required)
•	Pedals & cycling shoes (optional)
•	Enthusiasm for learning something new
•	Cash/check for the session and rental fee
•	Cash for the raffle!!!

Cost of the session:
Beginner Session is $10
Bike Rental is $5
(All proceeds from the session go toward maintenance and upkeep of the track and the rental bikes)
Rain Cancels (Rain Date TBD if needed)
Arrive around 1:00-1:30 to get a bike and sign in, session starts at 2.
course: Alkek Velodrome
registration: Registration is currently closed for February 6. Please sign up for February 20.

title: Sansom 66
description:
Is this the toughest endurance mountain bike event in North Texas? Many will attempt it, few will complete it. Time restrictions are tight, margin for error is slim and the course is difficult. Sansom Park is NOT your typical urban mountain bike trail. 1500' of elevation per each 11+ mile lap through loose rock climbs and descents and nary a straightaway over 200 feet long. The trail is fun and challenging and we're doing almost every bit of it!

Field is limited to a maximum of 100 participants. Event will be rescheduled if weather creates an issue. No refunds but entries can be transferred at no charge if your plans change.

This is a distance event with a timed cutoff(s) not a timed endurance event.

Solo (Elite) Century of 6 laps but with a cutoff based on 90 minute laps (must begin 6th lap by 4:30 pm). 6 laps is going to be very tough to complete. You don't have to be Pro or Cat 1 to participate but we recommend this field only to experienced single track endurance racers based on the technical difficulty of the course.

Solo (Sport) Half Century of 3 laps with no cutoff time. 3 laps in a day will be plenty tough for most mortals. This should be an extremely well rounded field.

2 Person Relay (Men, Women, Co-ed) 6 laps with a cutoff based on 90 minute laps. Relayers must alternate laps so each rider must ride 3 laps for the team to complete the course. No individual rider will be allowed to ride consecutive laps.
course: Marion Sansom Park singletrack moutain bike trail.
registration: Prereg only. No day of registration available.

title: Red River Riot
description:
The Red River Riot is back and better than ever with the focus being the best and most challenging route possible. This is not an official "race" so don't look for prize money, sag support, or even rules. Get your spot early to guarantee a shirt and a plate of Spinistry chow. There will NOT be any day of registration. Prereg only please.

We're going to give you a great route to follow that will cover up to 200 miles of dirt roads in the scenic Red River area of North Texas. Entry fee includes a great staging area, food/drinks, and will provide directions for everyone to find their way from Point A to Point Z. 

The long route will be around 140 miles The medium route will be around 80 miles We will also offer a mini route of around 35 miles for those who are gravel curious. Everyone will ride that first 35 mile loop so you can go out for more if you feel up to it.

This year we are introducing a true 200 mie "Double Century" option for the truly masochistic. More details on that as the pieces come together.

The most current information will most likely be on the Spinistry Facebook page or on Spinistry.com. See you there! REMINDER: This is a self supported ride. There WILL NOT be any aid stations or SAG wagons. Do not attempt this ride if you are uncomfortable being 20 miles from civilization with ZERO support

title: Midnight Massacre
description:
The original night time gravel grinder is back...bigger and badder than ever! We're sticking with the traditional short route for folks who want to maximize their party time as well as the longer route to keep riders out into the wee hours of the morning. This year's routes are almost entirely new with a bonus stop at Whiskey Hollow Distillery in Valley View!

Hey, it's summer in Texas and you wanna have fun on your bike right? This year's edition of the Midnight Massacre is sure to please everyone looking for that classic beat the heat in the middle of the night gravel grinder/party.

We're returning to our traditional staging area. This means staging is close toe MetroMess in Sanger but we're still far enough out for some great dirt roads! Spinistry chow (BBQ, beans, pico and more) as well as an appearance by B2D2 should guarantee a grand evening for all.

Routes are nearly finalized and feature a spectacular long route of 100 miles, a medium route of 70 miles and a very sweet 37 mile short loop. This is a self supported ride and we will not be providing SAG or refreshments on the course. Plan on carrying enough to get you through the full route and maybe a little more. You are welcome to have your own support for meet up along the route but we prefer not to have a bunch of support vehicles dusting up the dirt roads. DO NOT register if you are uncomfortable being in the middle of nowhere in the middle of the night by yourself.

Staging area is Railroad Ball Park 600 Railroad Ave Sanger, TX.
course: Primarily dirt and county roads in rural North Texas. Riders must obey all rules of the road per Texas statutes.
notes: This is not a race

title: Iceman's Challenge Gravel Pursuit
description:
The Iceman's Challenge Gravel Pursuit Adventure Event is the annual winter signature gravel adventure ride and race hosted by The Bear Mountain Bike and Outdoor Stores.  The Iceman's Challenge is held on the first Saturday in December and will be held on Saturday, December 3, 2016, at the historic Talbert Ranch in China Spring, Texas.


So, what the heck is a Gravel Pursuit?  A gravel pursuit event offers participants options to go at a race pace, go social, or meander down country roads enjoying the scenery.  Chose to do an adventure race or an adventure ride from our awesome selection of routes, and bring your favorite type of bike you love to ride. The obvious objective is for each participant to have fun and enjoy the challenge of cycling in the great outdoors on their adventure bike on remote roads in McLennan and Bosque Counties.


The 2016 Iceman's Challenge offers four routes having miles of beautiful gravel roads, some shaded by trees, some on sunlit country roads that meander through ranches, by rivers, creeks, and streams, with hardly a car to be seen except maybe a few old ranch pickup trucks and a couple of tractors with farm implements.  

For event details and specific information regarding event schedule, maps, locations, FAQs, event rules, and contact information please go to our officlal website at http://www.icemanschallenge.com.  For important event updates and current information please follow us on our Facebook Page at  https://www.facebook.com/Icemans-Challenge-Road-to-Hell-Gravel-Advenuture-Ride-1655202051402244/
course: The event will offer four courses held on approximately 80-85% gravel roads and 15-20% paved roads.  The roads vary in surface condition from good gravel, to small cinder like sand, to dirt, to bigger rock, to some rutted wash out, to chip seal and smooth asphalt pavement. The surface will be everything from tight gravel in lower elevations to larger rock, water crossings, and some rutted muddy roads from water runoff throughout the course.  Participants may choose from four separate courses:  (1)  the 82 mile Frozen Margarita Gravel Pursuit, the 61 Mile Big Brew Gravel Pursuit, the 48 Mile Wine Cooler Gravel Pursuit, and the 31 Mile Sarsaprilla Gravel Pursuit.
registration:
Register at our official registration page at BikeReg.com.  at https://www.bikereg.com/icemans-challenge-gravel-pursuit

Official online registration opens on Friday, September 2, 2016, and will closes at 12:00 pm/midnight on Thursday, December 1, 2016.  On site registration will begin on Friday afternoon at 4:00 p.m., December 2, 2016, at the Bear Mountain Bike Shop and continue to Saturday morning at 6:30 a.m., December 3, 2016, at the Talbert Ranch Barn located 5037 Talbert Ranch Road, China Spring, Texas. Take advantage of our early discount registration and regular registration please register before Friday, November 25, 2016,  Late registration and fee price increases will begin on Saturday, November 26 - December 1, 2016.  Online registration closes on Thursday, December 1, 2016, at 12:00 pm/midnight.

Notice: This event will be held rain or shine, no cancellations, NO REFUNDS.
notes:
Event Rules & Requirements:

    All participants must sign our official legal waiver at registration and at the event prior to participation in the Iceman's Challenge - Road to Hell Gravel Adventure Ride.
    All riders shall wear a helmet certified by CPSC or ASTM whenever they are on their bicycles participating in the Iceman's Challenge events.
    All ride participants and volunteers shall conduct themselves in a safe and prudent manner.
    Follow provided route at all times.  The course will be posted online prior to the event and clue sheets will be distributed.
     Every rider, without exception, must obey all traffic laws, including stopping at all stop signs and signals. Riders shall stay to the right of the road as conditions permit and ride single file whenever prudent (e.g. motor vehicle traffic is present).
    All riders must check in prior to starting and check out when off the course.  You must notify the event director or volunteer if you withdraw from the race.
    Cyclists shall not use cell phones for conversation or texting while riding. If cell phone use is necessary the cyclist must pull off the road for the duration of the conversation.
    The Iceman's Challenge officials recommend all riders carry cell phones, and as mentioned in the Communications Section, all riders should recognize that cell phone service may not be available in all areas traversed by the ride. In the event of a medical emergency, riders should immediately call 911 via cell phone or other practical means, (e.g. residential telephone line). Riders should then contact the Ride Director per the telephone numbers provided on the turn-by-turn directions provided at check-in.
    Use common sense at all times.
    All participating cyclists are responsible for food, water, repair of their bicycles, and all support matters as stated herein.
    Cyclists must not be under the influence of drugs or alcohol while participating in the ride event.
    The Iceman's Challenge organizers reserve the right to alter these rules as unforeseen circumstances arise for the safety and well being of all involved.
